# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fred-kommers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fred-kommers/1913-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1913 throughout the world.
[src:fred-kommers/1914-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1914 throughout the world.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:fred-kommers/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:fred-kommers/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In baseball, **batting average** (**BA**) is determined by dividing a player's hits by their total at-bats.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] It is usually rounded to three decimal places and read without the decimal: A player with a batting average of .300 is said to be "batting three hundred".
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] If necessary to break ties, batting averages could be taken beyond the .001 measurement.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In this context, .001 is considered a "point", such that a .235 batter is five points higher than a .230 batter.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Henry Chadwick, an English statistician raised on cricket, was an influential figure in the early history of baseball.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] He is credited with creating the modern box score, in 1859, and the practice of denoting a strikeout with a "K".
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In 1869, another early baseball proponent, Alfred Wright, published an end-of-season summary that included the average number of times a batter had "clean" hits on a *per game* basis.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In 1871, a writer for the *New York Clipper*, Hervie Dobson, proposed that a batter's "average is found by dividing his total 'times first base on clean hits' by his total number of times he went to the bat"—hits divided by at bats.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] By 1874, some teams were calculating batting averages, and by 1876, it was being calculated by all teams of the National League.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In modern times, a season batting average of .300 or higher is considered to be excellent, and an average higher than .400 is a nearly unachievable goal.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The last Major League Baseball (MLB) player to do so, with enough plate appearances to qualify for the batting championship, was Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox, who hit .406 in 1941.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Note that batting averages are rounded; entering the final day of the 1941 season, Williams was at 179-for-448, which is .39955 and would have been recorded as .400 via rounding.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] However, Williams played in both games of a doubleheader, went 6-for-8, and ended the season 185-for-456, which is .40570 and becomes .406 when rounded.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Since 1941, no American League or National League player has hit .400 or above—the highest single-season average in those leagues has been .394 by Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres in 1994.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Wade Boggs hit .401 over a 162-game span with Boston from June 9, 1985, to June 6, 1986, but never hit above .368 for an MLB season.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] There have been numerous attempts to explain the disappearance of the .400 hitter, with one of the more rigorous discussions of this question appearing in Stephen Jay Gould's 1996 book *Full House*.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Josh Gibson hit .466 in 1943 while playing for the Homestead Grays of the Negro National League, one of several leagues within Negro league baseball that are now recognized by MLB.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Gibson holds the record for highest major-league career batting average at .371, four points higher than Ty Cobb, who has the second-highest career average at .367.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The record for lowest career batting average for a player with more than 2,500 at-bats belongs to Bill Bergen, a catcher who played from 1901 to 1911 and recorded a .170 average in 3,028 career at-bats.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Hugh Duffy, who played from 1888 to 1906, is credited with the highest single-season batting average, having hit .440 in 1894.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era (post-1900) record for highest batting average for a season is held by Nap Lajoie, who hit .426 in 1901, the first year of play for the American League.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The modern-era record for the lowest batting average for a player that qualified for the batting title is held by Chris Davis, who hit .168 in 2018.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] While finishing six plate appearances short of qualifying for the batting title, Adam Dunn of the Chicago White Sox hit .159 for the 2011 season, nine points lower than the record.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The highest batting average for a rookie was .408 in 1911 by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The league batting average in MLB for the 2018 season was .248, with the highest modern-era MLB average being .296 in 1930, and the lowest being .237 in 1968.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] For non-pitchers, a batting average below .230 is often considered poor, and one below .200 is usually unacceptable.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] This latter level is sometimes referred to as "The Mendoza Line", named for Mario Mendoza—a lifetime .215 hitter but a good defensive shortstop.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Sabermetrics, the study of baseball statistics, considers batting average a weak measure of performance because it does not correlate as well as other measures to runs scored, thereby causing it to have little predictive value.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Batting average does not take into account bases on balls (walks) or power, whereas other statistics such as on-base percentage and slugging percentage have been specifically designed to measure such concepts.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Adding these statistics together form a player's on-base plus slugging or "OPS".
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] This is commonly seen as a much better, though not perfect, indicator of a player's overall batting ability as it is a measure of hitting for average, hitting for power, and drawing walks.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In 1887, bases on balls (walks) were counted as hits by the major leagues in existence at the time.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] This inflated batting averages, with 11 players batting .400 or better, and the experiment was abandoned the following season.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In rare instances, players have concluded their careers with a perfect batting average of 1.000—through the 2021 season, there were 94 such players in major-league history, 83 of whom recorded exactly one hit in one at bat.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Only one player with a 1.000 average has had three hits—outfielder John Paciorek (1963), who had three hits in three at bats; he also had two walks, and scored four runs.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Players who had two hits in their only two at bats include: pitcher Frank O'Connor (1893), catcher Mike Hopkins (1902), pitcher Doc Tonkin (1907), pitcher Hal Deviney (1920), pitcher Fred Schemanske (1923), pitcher Chet Kehn (1942), second baseman Steve Biras (1944), and pitcher Jason Roach (2003).
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Pitcher Esteban Yan, who played in 472 major-league games from 1996 to 2006, mainly in the American League (where pitchers have rarely batted since the introduction of the designated hitter in 1973), also had two hits in his only two at bats, one a home run.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The MLB batting averages championships (often referred to as "the batting title") are awarded annually to the player in each league with the highest batting average.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Ty Cobb holds the MLB and American League (AL) record for most batting titles, officially winning 11 in his career.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The National League (NL) record of eight batting titles is shared by Honus Wagner and Tony Gwynn.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] This is officially Rule 10.22(a), but it is also known as the "Tony Gwynn rule" because the Padres' player won the batting crown in 1996 with a .353 average on just 498 plate appearances (i.e., he was four short).
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Gwynn was awarded the title since he would have led the league even if he had gone 0-for-4 in those missing plate appearances.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] His average would have dropped to .349, five points better than second-place Ellis Burks' .344.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In 2012, a one-time amendment to the rule was made to disqualify Melky Cabrera from the title.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Cabrera requested that he be disqualified after serving a suspension that season for a positive testosterone test.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] He had batted .346 with 501 plate appearances, and the original rule would have awarded him the title over San Francisco Giants teammate Buster Posey, who won batting .336.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] The highest recorded single-season batting average in Minor League Baseball is .462, accomplished by Gary Redus in 1978, when he played for the Billings Mustangs, an affiliate of the Cincinnati Reds in the Rookie Advanced-level Pioneer League.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Redus was 117-for-253 in 68 games, as the Pioneer League only plays from June to early September.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Redus went on to play in MLB from 1982 through 1994, batting .252 during his MLB career.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the leader in career batting average is Isao Harimoto, a member of the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame, who hit .319 in his NPB career.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Ichiro Suzuki batted .353 in NPB, but does not have enough NPB career at-bats to qualify for the league's title.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Sadaharu Oh had a batting average of .355 in 1973 season.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Randy Bass had a batting average of .389 in 1986 season.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] In KBO League (KBO), the leader in career batting average is Jung-hoo Lee, who hit .340 in his KBO career and is currently an active player.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] Baek In-chun had a batting average of .412 in 1982 season.
[src:fred-kommers/batting-average-baseball] This is the highest batting average of one season in KBO League.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was incorporated as a city in 1837 near a portage between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It grew rapidly in the mid-19th century.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed several square miles and left more than 100,000 homeless, but Chicago's population continued to grow.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago made noted contributions to urban planning and architecture, such as the Chicago School, the development of the City Beautiful movement, and the steel-framed skyscraper.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is an international hub for finance, culture, commerce, industry, education, technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It has the largest and most diverse finance derivatives market in the world, generating 20% of all volume in commodities and financial futures alone.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] O'Hare International Airport is routinely ranked among the world's top ten busiest airports by passenger traffic, and the region is also the nation's railroad hub.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago area has one of the highest gross domestic products (GDP) of any urban region in the world, ranking sixth globally, generating over $919 billion in 2024.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's economy is diverse, with no single industry employing more than 14% of the workforce.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is a major destination for tourism, with nearly 57 million people visiting its cultural institutions, Lake Michigan beaches, restaurants, and other tourist sites in 2025.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's culture has made significant contributions to the visual arts, literature, film, theater, comedy (especially improvisational comedy), food, dance, and music (particularly jazz, blues, soul, hip-hop, gospel, industrial, and electronic dance music, especially house music).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and the Lyric Opera of Chicago, while the Art Institute of Chicago has an influential visual arts museum and art school.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago area is home to the University of Chicago, Northwestern University, and the University of Illinois Chicago, among other institutions of higher education.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It also hosts the Barack Obama Presidential Center.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Professional sports in Chicago include all major professional leagues, including two Major League Baseball teams.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city also hosts the Chicago Marathon, one of the World Marathon Majors.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The name *Chicago* is derived from a French rendering of the indigenous Miami–Illinois word *šikaakwa*, which was a name for a wild relative of onion and garlic known to modern botanists as *Allium tricoccum*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The first known reference to the site of the city of Chicago as "*Checagou*" was by Robert de La Salle around 1679 in a memoir.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Henri Joutel, in his journal of 1688, noted that the eponymous wild "garlic" grew profusely in the area.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city has had several nicknames throughout its history, such as the Windy City, Chi-Town, Second City, and City of the Big Shoulders.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the mid-18th century, the area was inhabited by the Potawatomi, an indigenous tribe who had succeeded the Miami, Sauk and Meskwaki peoples in this region.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The first known permanent settler in Chicago was a trader, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Du Sable was of African descent, perhaps born in the French colony of Saint-Domingue (Haiti), and he established the settlement in the 1780s.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] He is commonly known as the "Founder of Chicago".
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1795, following the victory of the new United States in the Northwest Indian War, an area that was to be part of Chicago was turned over to the U.S. for a military post by native tribes in accordance with the Treaty of Greenville.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Army constructed Fort Dearborn, which was destroyed during the War of 1812 in the Battle of Fort Dearborn by the Potawatomi before being later rebuilt.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] After the War of 1812, the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi tribes ceded additional land to the United States in the 1816 Treaty of St.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Potawatomi were forcibly removed from their land after the 1833 Treaty of Chicago and sent west of the Mississippi River as part of the federal policy of Indian removal.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] On August 12, 1833, the Town of Chicago was organized with a population of about 200.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Within seven years it grew to more than 6,000 people.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] On June 15, 1835, the first public land sales began with Edmund Dick Taylor as Receiver of Public Monies.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The City of Chicago was incorporated on Saturday, March 4, 1837, and for several decades was the world's fastest-growing city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] As the site of the Chicago Portage, the city became an important transportation hub between the eastern and western United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's first railway, Galena and Chicago Union Railroad, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal opened in 1848.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The canal allowed steamboats and sailing ships on the Great Lakes to connect to the Mississippi River.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A flourishing economy brought residents from rural communities and immigrants from abroad.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Manufacturing and retail and finance sectors became dominant, influencing the American economy.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago Board of Trade (established 1848) listed the first-ever standardized "exchange-traded" forward contracts, which were called futures contracts.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the 1850s, Chicago gained national political prominence as the home of Senator Stephen Douglas, the champion of the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the "popular sovereignty" approach to the issue of the spread of slavery.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] These issues also helped propel another Illinoisan, Abraham Lincoln, to the national stage.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Lincoln was nominated in Chicago for U.S. president at the 1860 Republican National Convention, which was held in a purpose-built auditorium called the Wigwam.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] He defeated Douglas in the general election, and this set the stage for the American Civil War.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] To accommodate rapid population growth and demand for better sanitation, the city improved its infrastructure.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In February 1856, Chicago's Common Council approved Chesbrough's plan to build the United States' first comprehensive sewerage system.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The project raised much of central Chicago to a new grade with the use of jackscrews for raising buildings.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] While elevating Chicago, and at first improving the city's health, the untreated sewage and industrial waste now flowed into the Chicago River, and subsequently into Lake Michigan, polluting the city's primary freshwater source.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city responded by tunneling two miles (3.2 km) out into Lake Michigan to newly built water cribs.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1900, the problem of sewage contamination was largely resolved when the city completed a major engineering feat.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It reversed the flow of the Chicago River so that the water flowed away from Lake Michigan rather than into it.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] This project began with the construction and improvement of the Illinois and Michigan Canal, and was completed with the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal that connects to the Illinois River, which flows into the Mississippi River.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] On October 8, 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6.4 km) long and 1-mile (1.6 km) wide, a large section of the city at the time.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] At least 300 people were killed and over 100,000 were left homeless from the fire.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] However, much of the city, including railroads and stockyards, survived intact, and from the ruins of the previous wooden structures arose more modern constructions of steel and stone.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] These set a precedent for worldwide construction.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] During its rebuilding period, Chicago constructed the world's first skyscraper in 1885, using steel-skeleton construction.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Labor conflicts followed the industrial boom and the rapid expansion of the labor pool during the Gilded Age, including the Haymarket affair on May 4, 1886, and in 1894 the Pullman Strike.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Anarchist and socialist groups played prominent roles in creating very large and highly organized labor actions.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Concern for social problems among Chicago's immigrant poor led Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr to found Hull House in 1889.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Programs that were developed there became a model for the new field of social work.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] During the 1870s and 1880s, Chicago attained national stature as the leader in the movement to improve public health.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] City laws and later, state laws that upgraded standards for the medical profession and fought urban epidemics of cholera, smallpox, and yellow fever were both passed and enforced.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] These laws became templates for public health reform in other cities and states.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city established many large, well-landscaped municipal parks, which also included public sanitation facilities.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The chief advocate for improving public health in Chicago was John H.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Rauch established a plan for Chicago's park system in 1866.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] He created Lincoln Park by closing a cemetery filled with shallow graves, and in 1867, in response to an outbreak of cholera he helped establish a new Chicago Board of Health.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Ten years later, he became the secretary and then the president of the first Illinois State Board of Health, which carried out most of its activities in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the 1800s, Chicago became the nation's railroad hub, and by 1910 over 20 railroads operated passenger service out of six different downtown terminals.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1883, Chicago's railway managers needed a general time convention, so they developed the standardized system of North American time zones.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] This system for telling time spread throughout the continent.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The desire to join the city was driven by municipal services that the city could provide its residents.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1893, Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition on former marshland at the present location of Jackson Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Exposition drew 27.5 million visitors, and is considered the most influential world's fair in history.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city's municipal device, a Y within a circle, was the result of a contest run by the *Chicago Tribune* in 1892, in anticipation of the Columbian Exposition.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The University of Chicago, formerly at another location, moved to the same South Side location in 1892.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The term "midway" for a fair or carnival referred originally to the Midway Plaisance, a strip of park land that still runs through the University of Chicago campus and connects the Washington and Jackson Parks.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's flourishing economy attracted huge numbers of new immigrants from Europe and migrants from the Eastern United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Of the total population in 1900, more than 77% were either foreign-born or born in the United States of foreign parentage.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Germans, Irish, Poles, Swedes, and Czechs made up nearly two-thirds of the foreign-born population (by 1900, whites were 98.1% of the city's population).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] During World War I and the 1920s there was a major expansion in industry.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the Southern United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Between 1910 and 1930, the African American population of Chicago increased dramatically, from 44,103 to 233,903.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] This Great Migration had an immense cultural impact, called the Chicago Black Renaissance, part of the New Negro Movement, in art, literature, and music.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Continuing racial tensions and violence in the city, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919, also occurred.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The ratification of the 18th amendment to the Constitution in 1919 made the production and sale (including exportation) of alcoholic beverages illegal in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] This ushered in the beginning of what is known as the gangster era, a time that roughly spans from 1919 until 1933 when Prohibition was repealed.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The 1920s saw gangsters, including Al Capone, Dion O'Banion, Bugs Moran and Tony Accardo battle law enforcement and each other on the streets of Chicago during the Prohibition era.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was the location of the infamous St.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Valentine's Day Massacre in 1929, when Al Capone sent men to gun down members of a rival gang, North Side, led by Bugs Moran, leaving seven rival members dead.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] From 1920 to 1921, the city was affected by a series of tenant rent strikes, which led to the formation of the Chicago Tenants Protective association, passage of the Kessenger tenant laws, and of a heat ordinance that legally required flats to be kept above 68 °F during winter months by landlords.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was the first American city to have a homosexual-rights organization.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The organization, formed in 1924, was called the Society for Human Rights.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It produced the first American publication for homosexuals, *Friendship and Freedom*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Police and political pressure caused the organization to disband.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Great Depression brought unprecedented suffering to Chicago, in no small part due to the city's heavy reliance on heavy industry.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Notably, industrial areas on the south side and neighborhoods lining both branches of the Chicago River were devastated; by 1933 over 50% of industrial jobs in the city had been lost, and unemployment rates amongst blacks and Latinos in the city were over 40%.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Republican political machine in Chicago was utterly destroyed by the economic crisis, and every mayor since 1931 has been a Democrat.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] From 1928 to 1933, the city witnessed a tax revolt, and the city was unable to meet payroll or provide relief efforts.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The fiscal crisis was resolved by 1933, and at the same time, federal relief funding began to flow into Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago was also a hotbed of labor activism, with Unemployed Councils contributing heavily in the early depression to create solidarity for the poor and demand relief; these organizations were created by socialist and communist groups.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By 1935, the Workers Alliance of America began organizing the poor, workers, the unemployed.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the spring of 1937 Republic Steel Works witnessed the Memorial Day massacre of 1937 in the neighborhood of East Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1933, Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak was fatally wounded in Miami, Florida, during a failed assassination attempt on President-elect Franklin D.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1933 and 1934, the city celebrated its centennial by hosting the Century of Progress International Exposition World's Fair.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The theme of the fair was technological innovation over the century since Chicago's founding.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] During World War II, the city of Chicago alone produced more steel than the United Kingdom every year from 1939 – 1945, and more than Nazi Germany from 1943 – 1945.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Great Migration, which had been on pause due to the Depression, resumed at an even faster pace in the second wave, as hundreds of thousands of blacks from the South arrived in the city to work in the steel mills, railroads, and shipping yards.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] On December 2, 1942, physicist Enrico Fermi conducted the world's first controlled nuclear reaction at the University of Chicago as part of the top-secret Manhattan Project.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] This led to the creation of the atomic bomb by the United States, which it used in World War II in 1945.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Daley, a Democrat, was elected in 1955, in the era of machine politics.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1956, the city conducted its last major expansion when it annexed the land under O'Hare airport, including a small portion of DuPage County.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By the 1960s, white residents in several neighborhoods left the city for the suburban areas – in many American cities, a process known as white flight – as Blacks continued to move beyond the Black Belt.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] While home loan discriminatory redlining against blacks continued, the real estate industry practiced what became known as blockbusting, completely changing the racial composition of whole neighborhoods.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Structural changes in industry, such as globalization and job outsourcing, caused heavy job losses for lower-skilled workers.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] At its peak during the 1960s, some 250,000 workers were employed in the steel industry in Chicago, but the steel crisis of the 1970s and 1980s reduced this number to just 28,000 in 2015.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1966, Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Raby led the Chicago Freedom Movement, which culminated in agreements between Mayor Richard J.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Two years later, the city hosted the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention, which featured physical confrontations both inside and outside the convention hall, with anti-war protesters, journalists and bystanders being beaten by police.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Major construction projects, including the Sears Tower (now known as the Willis Tower, which in 1974 became the world's tallest building), University of Illinois at Chicago, McCormick Place, and O'Hare International Airport, were undertaken during Richard J.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1979, Jane Byrne, the city's first female mayor, was elected.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] She was notable for temporarily moving into the crime-ridden Cabrini-Green housing project and leading Chicago's school system out of a financial crisis.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1983, Harold Washington became the first black mayor of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Washington's first term in office directed attention to poor and previously neglected minority neighborhoods.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] He was re‑elected in 1987 but died of a heart attack soon after.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Washington was succeeded by 6th ward alderperson Eugene Sawyer, who was elected by the Chicago City Council and served until a special election.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] His accomplishments included improvements to parks and creating incentives for sustainable development, as well as closing Meigs Field in the middle of the night and destroying the runways.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] After successfully running for re-election five times, and becoming Chicago's longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Daley declined to run for a seventh term.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1992, a construction accident near the Kinzie Street Bridge produced a breach connecting the Chicago River to a tunnel below, which was part of an abandoned freight tunnel system extending throughout the downtown Loop district.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The tunnels filled with 250 million US gallons (1,000,000 m3) of water, affecting buildings throughout the district and forcing a shutdown of electrical power.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The area was shut down for three days and some buildings did not reopen for weeks; losses were estimated at $1.95 billion.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] On February 23, 2011, Rahm Emanuel, a former White House Chief of Staff and member of the House of Representatives, won the mayoral election.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Emanuel was sworn in as mayor on May 16, 2011, and won re-election in 2015.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Lori Lightfoot, the city's first African American woman mayor and its first openly LGBTQ mayor, was elected to succeed Emanuel as mayor in 2019.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] All three city-wide elective offices were held by women (and women of color) for the first time in Chicago history: in addition to Lightfoot, the city clerk was Anna Valencia and the city treasurer was Melissa Conyears-Ervin.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] On May 15, 2023, Brandon Johnson assumed office as the 57th mayor of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is located in northeastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of freshwater Lake Michigan.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in both the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city rests on a continental divide at the site of the Chicago Portage, connecting the Mississippi River and the Great Lakes watersheds.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In addition to it lying beside Lake Michigan, two rivers—the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side—flow either entirely or partially through the city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's history and economy are closely tied to its proximity to Lake Michigan.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] While the Chicago River historically handled much of the region's waterborne cargo, today's huge lake freighters use the city's Lake Calumet Harbor on the South Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The lake also provides another positive effect: moderating Chicago's climate, making waterfront neighborhoods slightly warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] When Chicago was founded in 1837, most of the early building was around the mouth of the Chicago River, as can be seen on a map of the city's original 58 blocks.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The overall grade of the city's central, built-up areas is relatively consistent with the natural flatness of its overall natural geography, generally exhibiting only slight differentiation otherwise.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The average land elevation is 579 ft (176.5 m) above sea level.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] While measurements vary somewhat, the lowest points are along the lake shore at 578 ft (176.2 m), while the highest point, at 672 ft (205 m), is the morainal ridge of Blue Island in the city's far south side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Lake Shore Drive runs adjacent to a large portion of Chicago's waterfront.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Some of the parks along the waterfront include Lincoln Park, Grant Park, Burnham Park, and Jackson Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] There are 24 public beaches across 26 miles (42 km) of the waterfront.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Landfill extends into portions of the lake providing space for Navy Pier, Northerly Island, the Museum Campus, and large portions of the McCormick Place Convention Center.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Most of the city's high-rise commercial and residential buildings are close to the waterfront.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] An informal name for the entire Chicago metropolitan area is "Chicagoland", which generally means the city and all its suburbs, though different organizations have slightly different definitions.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Major sections of the city include the central business district, called the Loop, and the North, South, and West Sides.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The North Side is the city's most densely populated residential section, and many high-rises are on this side of the city along the lakefront.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The South Side is the city's largest section, encompassing roughly 60% of its land area.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The South Side contains most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the late 1920s, sociologists at the University of Chicago subdivided the city into 75 distinct community areas, plus O'Hare in 1956 and Edgewater in 1980 for a total of 77.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The community areas can further be subdivided into over 200 informally defined neighborhoods.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's streets were laid out in a street grid that grew from the city's original townsite plot, which was bounded by Lake Michigan on the east, North Avenue on the north, Wood Street on the west, and 22nd Street on the south.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Streets following the Public Land Survey System section lines later became arterial streets in outlying sections.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] As new additions to the city were platted, city ordinance required them to be laid out with eight streets to the mile in one direction and sixteen in the other direction, about one street per 200 meters in one direction and one street per 100 meters in the other direction.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The grid's regularity provided an efficient means of developing new real estate property.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A scattering of diagonal streets, many of them originally Native American trails, also cross the city (Elston, Milwaukee, Ogden, Lincoln, etc.).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Many additional diagonal streets were recommended in the Plan of Chicago, but only the extension of Ogden Avenue was ever constructed.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 2021, Chicago was ranked the fourth-most walkable large city in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Many of the city's residential streets have a wide patch of grass or trees between the street and the sidewalk itself.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] This helps to keep pedestrians on the sidewalk further away from the street traffic.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's Western Avenue is the longest continuous urban street in the world.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Other notable streets include Michigan Avenue, State Street, 95th Street, Cicero Avenue, Clark Street, and Belmont Avenue.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The City Beautiful movement inspired Chicago's boulevards and parkways.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The destruction caused by the Great Chicago Fire led to the largest building boom in the history of the nation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1885, the first steel-framed high-rise building, the Home Insurance Building, rose in the city as Chicago ushered in the skyscraper era, which would then be followed by many other cities around the world.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Today, Chicago's skyline is among the world's tallest and densest.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Some of the United States' tallest towers are located in Chicago; Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) is the third tallest building in the Western Hemisphere after One World Trade Center, and Central Park Tower.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Loop's historic buildings include the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Fine Arts Building, 35 East Wacker, and the Chicago Building, 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments by Mies van der Rohe.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Many other architects have left their impression on the Chicago skyline such as Daniel Burnham, Louis Sullivan, Charles B.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Merchandise Mart, once the largest building in the world, had its own zip code until 2008, and stands near the junction of the North and South branches of the Chicago River.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Presently, the four tallest buildings in the city are Willis Tower (formerly the Sears Tower, also a building with its own zip code), Trump International Hotel and Tower, the Aon Center (previously the Standard Oil Building), and the John Hancock Center.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Industrial districts, such as some areas on the South Side, the areas along the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal, and the Northwest Indiana area are clustered.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago gave its name to the Chicago School and was home to the Prairie School, two movements in architecture.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Multiple kinds and scales of houses, townhouses, condominiums, and apartment buildings can be found throughout Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Large swaths of the city's residential areas away from the lake are characterized by brick bungalows built from the early 20th century through the end of World War II.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is also a prominent center of the Polish Cathedral style of church architecture.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Chicago suburb of Oak Park was home to famous architect Frank Lloyd Wright, who had designed The Robie House located near the University of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A popular tourist activity is to take an architecture boat tour along the Chicago River.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is famous for its outdoor public art with donors establishing funding for such art as far back as Benjamin Ferguson's 1905 trust.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A number of Chicago's public art works are by modern figurative artists.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Some events which shaped the city's history have also been memorialized by art works, including the Great Northern Migration (Saar) and the centennial of statehood for Illinois.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Finally, two fountains near the Loop also function as monumental works of art: Plensa's Crown Fountain as well as Burnham and Bennett's Buckingham Fountain.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city mostly lies within the typical hot-summer humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*), and experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with frequent heat waves.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The July daily average temperature is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C), with afternoon temperatures peaking at 84.5 °F (29.2 °C).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In a normal summer, temperatures reach at least 90 °F (32 °C) on 17 days, with lakefront locations staying cooler when winds blow off the lake.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Blizzards do occur, such as in winter 2011.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The normal winter high from December through March is about 36 °F (2 °C).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] January and February are the coldest months.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A polar vortex in January 2019 nearly broke the city's cold record of −27 °F (−33 °C), which was set on January 20, 1985.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Measurable snowfall can continue through the first or second week of April.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, short seasons, typically with low humidity.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Dew point temperatures in the summer range from an average of 55.8 °F (13.2 °C) in June to 61.7 °F (16.5 °C) in July.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] They can reach nearly 80 °F (27 °C), such as during the July 2019 heat wave.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The city lies within USDA plant hardiness zone 6a, transitioning to 5b in the suburbs.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] According to the National Weather Service, Chicago's highest official temperature reading of 105 °F (41 °C) was recorded on July 24, 1934.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Midway Airport reached 109 °F (43 °C) one day prior and recorded a heat index of 125 °F (52 °C) during the 1995 heatwave.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The lowest official temperature of −27 °F (−33 °C) was recorded on January 20, 1985, at O'Hare Airport.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Most of the city's rainfall is brought by thunderstorms, averaging 38 a year.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The region is prone to severe thunderstorms during the spring and summer which can produce large hail, damaging winds, and occasionally tornadoes.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Notably, the F4 Oak Lawn tornado moved through the South Side of the city on April 21, 1967, moving onto Lake Michigan as a waterspout.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Downtown Chicago was struck by an F3 tornado on May 6, 1876, again moving out over Lake Michigan.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Like other major cities, Chicago experiences an urban heat island, making the city and its suburbs milder than surrounding rural areas, especially at night and in winter.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Northeast winds from wintertime cyclones departing south of the region sometimes bring the city lake-effect snow.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] During its first hundred years, Chicago was one of the fastest-growing cities in the world.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] When founded in 1833, fewer than 200 people had settled on what was then the American frontier.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By the time of its first census, seven years later, the population had reached over 4,000.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the forty years from 1850 to 1890, the city's population grew from slightly under 30,000 to over 1 million.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By the 1890 census, Chicago was the second most populous city in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By 1900, it was the fifth largest in the world behind Berlin, Paris, New York, and London, and the largest city founded in the prior century.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Within sixty years of the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, the population went from about 300,000 to over 3 million, and reached its highest ever recorded population of 3.6 million for the 1950 census.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] To these ethnic groups, the basis of the city's industrial working class, were added an additional influx of African Americans from the American South as part of the Great Migration—with Chicago's black population doubling between 1910 and 1920 and doubling again between 1920 and 1930.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago has a significant Bosnian population, many of whom arrived in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, the great majority of African Americans moving to Chicago settled in a so‑called "Black Belt" on the city's South Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A large number of blacks also settled on the West Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By 1930, two-thirds of Chicago's black population lived in sections of the city which were 90% black in racial composition.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Around that time, the block of 4600 Winthrop Avenue in the Uptown neighborhood was the only one in the neighborhood on which African Americans could live or open establishments.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's South Side emerged as United States second-largest urban black concentration, following New York's Harlem.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 1990, Chicago's South Side and the adjoining south suburbs constituted the largest black majority region in the entire United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Since the 1980s, Chicago has had a massive exodus of African Americans (primarily from the South and West sides) to its suburbs or outside its metropolitan area.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The above average crime and cost of living were leading reasons for the fast declining African American population in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Most of Chicago's foreign-born population were born in Mexico, Poland or India.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] A 2020 study estimated the total Jewish population of the Chicago metropolitan area, both religious and irreligious, at 319,500.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago's population declined in the latter half of the 20th century, from over 3.6 million in 1950 down to under 2.7 million by 2010.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] By the time of the official census count in 1990, it was overtaken by Los Angeles as the United States' second largest city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] It then saw a rise in population for the 2000 census, a decrease in 2010, and another increase for the 2020 census.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] According to U.S. census estimates as of July 2019, Chicago's largest racial or ethnic group is non-Hispanic White at 32.8% of the population, Blacks at 30.1% and the Hispanic population at 29.0% of the population.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago became a "de jure" sanctuary city in 2012 when Mayor Rahm Emanuel and the City Council passed the Welcoming City Ordinance.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Census Bureau's American Community Survey data estimates for 2022, the median income for a household in the city was $70,386, and the per capita income was $45,449.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Male full-time workers had a median income of $68,870 versus $60,987 for females.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] About 17.2% of the population lived below the poverty line.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 2018, Chicago ranked seventh globally for the highest number of ultra-high-net-worth residents with roughly 3,300 residents worth more than $30 million.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Persons who did not report or classify an ancestry were 548,790.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago has the third-largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ) population in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Since the 2013 legalization of same-sex marriage in Illinois, over 10,000 same-sex couples have wed in Illinois' Cook County, a majority of them in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is the first U.S. city to have a pro-gay organization and consistently ranks as one of the most LGBTQ-friendly cities in the nation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Lake View and Edgewater are historically the epicenters of LGBTQ culture in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] According to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Chicago (71%), with the city being the fourth-most religious metropolis in the United States after Dallas, Atlanta and Houston.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Roman Catholicism and Protestantism are the largest branches (34% and 35% respectively), followed by Eastern Orthodoxy and Jehovah's Witnesses with 1% each.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago also has a sizable non-Christian population.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Non-Christian groups include Irreligious (22%), Judaism (3%), Islam (2%), Buddhism (1%) and Hinduism (1%).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Chicago is the headquarters of several religious denominations, including the Evangelical Covenant Church and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The Fourth Presbyterian Church is one of the largest Presbyterian congregations in the United States based on memberships.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Since the 20th century Chicago has also been the headquarters of the Assyrian Church of the East.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] In 2014 the Catholic Church was the largest individual Christian denomination (34%), with the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago being the largest Catholic jurisdiction.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Evangelical Protestantism form the largest theological Protestant branch (16%), followed by Mainline Protestants (11%), and historically Black churches (8%).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Among denominational Protestant branches, Baptists formed the largest group in Chicago (10%); followed by Nondenominational (5%); Lutherans (4%); and Pentecostals (3%).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Non-Christian faiths accounted for 7% of the religious population in 2014.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Judaism has at least 261,000 adherents which is 3% of the population.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] The first two Parliament of the World's Religions in 1893 and 1993 were held in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Many international religious leaders have visited Chicago, including Mother Teresa, the Dalai Lama and Pope John Paul II in 1979.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p01] Pope Leo XIV was born in Chicago in 1955 and graduated from the Catholic Theological Union in Hyde Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has the third-largest gross metropolitan product in the United States—about $670.5 billion according to September 2017 estimates.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has also been rated as having the most balanced economy in the United States, due to its high level of diversification.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area has the third-largest science and engineering work force of any metropolitan area in the nation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago was the base of commercial operations for industrialists John Crerar, John Whitfield Bunn, Richard Teller Crane, Marshall Field, John Farwell, Julius Rosenwald, and many other commercial visionaries who laid the foundation for Midwestern and global industry.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is a major world financial center, with the second-largest central business district in the United States, following Midtown Manhattan.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is the seat of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, the Bank's Seventh District.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has major financial and futures exchanges, including the Chicago Stock Exchange, the Cboe Global Markets Options Exchange, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (the "Merc"), which is owned, along with the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT), by Chicago's CME Group.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2017, Chicago exchanges traded 4.7 billion in derivatives.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chase Bank has its commercial and retail banking headquarters in Chicago's Chase Tower.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Academically, Chicago has been influential through the Chicago school of economics, which fielded 12 Nobel Prize winners.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city and its surrounding metropolitan area contain the third-largest labor pool in the United States with about 4.63 million workers.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Illinois is home to 66 *Fortune* 1000 companies, including those in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city of Chicago also hosts 12 *Fortune* Global 500 companies and 17 *Financial Times* 500 companies.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city claims three Dow 30 companies: aerospace giant Boeing, which moved its headquarters from Seattle to the Chicago Loop in 2001; McDonald's; and Walgreens Boots Alliance.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] For six consecutive years from 2013 through 2018, Chicago was ranked the nation's top metropolitan area for corporate relocations.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] However, three *Fortune* 500 companies left Chicago in 2022, leaving the city with 35, still second to New York City.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Manufacturing, printing, publishing, and food processing also play major roles in the city's economy.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Several medical products and services companies are based in the Chicago area, including Baxter International, Boeing, Abbott Laboratories, and the Healthcare division of General Electric.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Prominent food companies based in Chicago include the world headquarters of Conagra, Ferrara Candy Company, Kraft Heinz, McDonald's, Mondelez International, and Quaker Oats.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has been a hub of the retail sector since its early development, with Montgomery Ward, Sears, and Marshall Field's.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Today the Chicago metropolitan area is the headquarters of several retailers, including Walgreens, Sears, Ace Hardware, Claire's, ULTA Beauty, and Crate & Barrel.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Tech companies based in the area include CDW, Uber Frieght, Zebra Technologies, Motorola Solutions, Motorola along with regional offices for Google, Salesforce, LinkedIn, and more.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago was also the site of the Schwinn Bicycle Company.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is a major world convention destination.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city's main convention center is McCormick Place.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] With its four interconnected buildings, it is the largest convention center in the nation and third-largest in the world.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] (behind Las Vegas and Orlando) in number of conventions hosted annually.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's minimum wage for non-tipped employees is one of the highest in the nation and reached $15 in 2021.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city's waterfront location and nightlife attracts residents and tourists alike.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Over a third of the city population is concentrated in the lakefront neighborhoods from Rogers Park in the north to South Shore in the south.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has many upscale dining establishments as well as many ethnic restaurant districts.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Downtown is the center of Chicago's financial, cultural, governmental, and commercial institutions and the site of Grant Park and many of the city's skyscrapers.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Many of the city's financial institutions, such as the CBOT and the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, are located within a section of downtown called "The Loop", which is an eight-block by five-block area of city streets that is encircled by elevated rail tracks.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The term "The Loop" is largely used by locals to refer to the entire downtown area as well.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The central area includes the Near North Side, the Near South Side, and the Near West Side, as well as the Loop.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] These areas contribute famous skyscrapers, abundant restaurants, shopping, museums, Soldier Field, convention facilities, parkland, and beaches.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Lincoln Park contains Lincoln Park Zoo and Lincoln Park Conservatory.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The River North Gallery District features the nation's largest concentration of contemporary art galleries outside of New York City.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Lake View is home to Boystown, the city's large LGBT nightlife and culture center.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Pride Parade, held the last Sunday in June, is one of the world's largest with over a million people in attendance.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] North Halsted Street is the main thoroughfare of Boystown.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The South Side neighborhood of Hyde Park is the home of former U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The neighborhood is home to the Barack Obama Presidential Center, a museum and library dedicated to his presidency.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] It also contains the University of Chicago, ranked one of the world's top ten universities, and the Museum of Science and Industry.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The 6-mile (9.7 km) long Burnham Park stretches along the waterfront of the South Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Two of the city's largest parks are also located on this side of the city: Jackson Park, bordering the waterfront, hosted the World's Columbian Exposition in 1893, and is the site of the aforementioned museum; and slightly west sits Washington Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The two parks themselves are connected by a wide strip of parkland called the Midway Plaisance, running adjacent to the University of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The South Side hosts one of the city's largest parades, the annual African American Bud Billiken Parade and Picnic, which travels through Bronzeville to Washington Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Ford Motor Company has an automobile assembly plant on the South Side in Hegewisch, and most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago are also on the South Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The West Side holds the Garfield Park Conservatory, one of the largest collections of tropical plants in any U.S. city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Prominent Latino cultural attractions found here include Humboldt Park's Institute of Puerto Rican Arts and Culture and the annual Puerto Rican People's Parade, as well as the National Museum of Mexican Art and St.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Near West Side holds the University of Illinois at Chicago and was once home to Oprah Winfrey's Harpo Studios, the site of which has been rebuilt as the global headquarters of McDonald's.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city's distinctive accent, made famous by its use in classic films like *The Blues Brothers* and television programs like the *Saturday Night Live* skit "Bill Swerski's Superfans", is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] This dialect can be found in other cities bordering the Great Lakes, such as Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee, and Buffalo, New York, and most prominently features a rearrangement of certain vowel sounds, such as the short "a" sound as in "cat", which can sound more like "kyet" to outsiders.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The accent remains well associated with the city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Renowned Chicago theater companies include the Goodman Theatre in the Loop; the Steppenwolf Theatre Company and Victory Gardens Theater in Lincoln Park; and the Chicago Shakespeare Theater at Navy Pier.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Broadway In Chicago offers Broadway-style entertainment at five theaters: the Nederlander Theatre, CIBC Theatre, Cadillac Palace Theatre, Auditorium Building of Roosevelt University, and Broadway Playhouse at Water Tower Place.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Polish language productions for Chicago's large Polish speaking population can be seen at the historic Gateway Theatre in Jefferson Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Since 1968, the Joseph Jefferson Awards are given annually to acknowledge excellence in theater in the Chicago area.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's theater community spawned modern improvisational theater, and includes the prominent groups The Second City and I.O.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Symphony Orchestra (CSO) performs at Symphony Center, and is recognized as one of the best orchestras in the world.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Also performing regularly at Symphony Center is the Chicago Sinfonietta, a more diverse and multicultural counterpart to the CSO.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In the summer, many outdoor concerts are given in Grant Park and Millennium Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Ravinia Festival, located 25 miles (40 km) north of Chicago, is the summer home of the CSO, and is a favorite destination for many Chicagoans.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Civic Opera House is home to the Lyric Opera of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Lithuanian Opera Company of Chicago was founded by Lithuanian Chicagoans in 1956, and presents operas in Lithuanian.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Joffrey Ballet and Chicago Festival Ballet perform in various venues, including the Harris Theater in Millennium Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has several other contemporary and jazz dance troupes, such as the Hubbard Street Dance Chicago and Chicago Dance Crash.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Other live-music genre which are part of the city's cultural heritage include Chicago blues, Chicago soul, jazz, and gospel.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is the birthplace of house music (a popular form of electronic dance music) and industrial music, and is the site of an influential hip hop scene.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In the 1980s and 90s, the city was the global center for house and industrial music, two forms of music created in Chicago, as well as being popular for alternative rock, punk, and new wave.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has been a center for rave culture, since the 1980s.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A flourishing independent rock music culture brought forth Chicago indie.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Annual festivals feature various acts, such as Lollapalooza and the Pitchfork Music Festival.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Lollapalooza originated in 1991 as a touring festival, but as of 2005 its home has been Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A 2007 report on the Chicago music industry by the University of Chicago Cultural Policy Center ranked Chicago third among metropolitan U.S. areas in "size of music industry" and fourth among all U.S. cities in "number of concerts and performances".
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has a distinctive fine art tradition.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] For much of the twentieth century, it nurtured a strong style of figurative surrealism, as in the works of Ivan Albright and Ed Paschke.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In 1968 and 1969, members of the Chicago Imagists, such as Roger Brown, Leon Golub, Robert Lostutter, Jim Nutt, and Barbara Rossi produced bizarre representational paintings.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Henry Darger is one of the most celebrated figures of outsider art.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2014, Chicago attracted 50.17 million domestic leisure travelers, 11.09 million domestic business travelers and 1.308 million overseas visitors.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] These visitors contributed more than US$13.7 billion to Chicago's economy.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Upscale shopping along the Magnificent Mile and State Street, thousands of restaurants, as well as Chicago's architecture, continue to draw tourists.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is the United States' third-largest convention destination.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A 2017 study by Walk Score ranked Chicago the sixth-most walkable of fifty largest cities in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Most conventions are held at McCormick Place, just south of Soldier Field.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Navy Pier, located just east of Streeterville, is 3,000 ft (910 m) long and houses retail stores, restaurants, museums, exhibition halls and auditoriums.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Ferris wheel first appeared at the World's Columbian Exposition, held in Chicago in 1893.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Willis Tower, formerly named Sears Tower, is a popular destination for tourists.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Among the city's museums are the Adler Planetarium & Astronomy Museum, the Field Museum of Natural History, and the Shedd Aquarium.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Museum Campus joins the southern section of Grant Park, which includes the renowned Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Buckingham Fountain anchors the downtown park along the lakefront.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The University of Chicago's Institute for the Study of Ancient Cultures, West Asia & North Africa has an extensive collection of ancient Egyptian and Near Eastern archaeological artifacts.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago lays claim to a large number of regional specialties that reflect the city's ethnic and working-class roots.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Included among these are its nationally renowned deep-dish pizza; this style is said to have originated at Pizzeria Uno.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago-style thin crust is also popular in the city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Certain Chicago pizza favorites include Lou Malnati's and Giordano's.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago-style hot dog, typically an all-beef hot dog, is loaded with an array of toppings that often includes pickle relish, yellow mustard, pickled sport peppers, tomato wedges, dill pickle spear and topped off with celery salt on a poppy seed bun.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Enthusiasts of the Chicago-style hot dog frown upon the use of ketchup as a garnish, but may prefer to add giardiniera.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A distinctly Chicago sandwich, the Italian beef sandwich is thinly sliced beef simmered in au jus and served on an Italian roll with sweet peppers or spicy giardiniera.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A popular modification is the Combo—an Italian beef sandwich with the addition of an Italian sausage.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Maxwell Street Polish is a grilled or deep-fried kielbasa—on a hot dog roll, topped with grilled onions, yellow mustard, and hot sport peppers.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicken Vesuvio is roasted bone-in chicken cooked in oil and garlic next to garlicky oven-roasted potato wedges and a sprinkling of green peas.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Puerto Rican-influenced jibarito is a sandwich made with flattened, fried green plantains instead of bread.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The mother-in-law is a tamale topped with chili and served on a hot dog bun.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The tradition of serving the Greek dish saganaki while aflame has its origins in Chicago's Greek community.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The appetizer, which consists of a square of fried cheese, is doused with Metaxa and flambéed table-side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago-style barbecue features hardwood smoked rib tips and hot links which were traditionally cooked in an aquarium smoker, a Chicago invention.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Annual festivals feature various Chicago signature dishes, such as Taste of Chicago and the Chicago Food Truck Festival.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] One of the world's most decorated restaurants and a recipient of three Michelin stars, Alinea is located in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Well-known chefs who have had restaurants in Chicago include: Charlie Trotter, Rick Tramonto, Grant Achatz, and Rick Bayless.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2003, *Robb Report* named Chicago the country's "most exceptional dining destination".
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago literature finds its roots in the city's tradition of lucid, direct journalism, lending to a strong tradition of social realism.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Narrative fiction of that time, much of it in the style of "high-flown romance" and "genteel realism", needed a new approach to describe the urban social, political, and economic conditions of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Nonetheless, Chicagoans worked hard to create a literary tradition that would stand the test of time, and create a "city of feeling" out of concrete, steel, vast lake, and open prairie.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Much notable Chicago fiction focuses on the city itself, with social criticism keeping exultation in check.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] At least three short periods in the history of Chicago have had a lasting influence on American literature.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] These include from the time of the Great Chicago Fire to about 1900, what became known as the Chicago Literary Renaissance in the 1910s and early 1920s, and the period of the Great Depression to the 1940s.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] What would become the influential *Poetry* magazine was founded in 1912 by Harriet Monroe, who was working as an art critic for the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The magazine discovered such poets as Gwendolyn Brooks, James Merrill, and John Ashbery.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Eliot's first professionally published poem, "The Love Song of J.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Alfred Prufrock", was first published by *Poetry*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Contributors have included Ezra Pound, William Butler Yeats, William Carlos Williams, Langston Hughes, and Carl Sandburg, among others.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The magazine was instrumental in launching the Imagist and Objectivist poetic movements.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, American poetry continued to evolve in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In the 1980s, a modern form of poetry performance began in Chicago, the poetry slam.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has two Major League Baseball (MLB) teams: the Chicago Cubs of the National League play in Wrigley Field on the North Side; and the Chicago White Sox of the American League play in Rate Field on the South Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The two teams have faced each other in a World Series only once, in 1906.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Cubs are the oldest Major League Baseball team to have never changed their city; they have played in Chicago since 1871.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] They had the dubious honor of having the longest championship drought in American professional sports, failing to win a World Series between 1908 and 2016.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The White Sox have played on the South Side continuously since 1901.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] They have won three World Series titles (1906, 1917, 2005) and six American League pennants, including the first in 1901.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Bears, one of the last two remaining charter members of the National Football League (NFL), have won nine NFL Championships, including the 1985 Super Bowl XX.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Bears play their home games at Soldier Field.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Bulls of the National Basketball Association (NBA) is one of the most recognized basketball teams in the world.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] During the 1990s, with Michael Jordan leading them, the Bulls won six NBA championships in eight seasons.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Blackhawks of the National Hockey League (NHL) began play in 1926, and are one of the "Original Six" teams of the NHL.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Blackhawks have won six Stanley Cups, including in 2010, 2013, and 2015.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Both the Bulls and the Blackhawks play at the United Center.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago Fire FC is a member of Major League Soccer (MLS) and plays at Soldier Field.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Fire have won one league title and four U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Open Cups, since their founding in 1997.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In 1994, the United States hosted a successful FIFA World Cup with games played at Soldier Field.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Stars FC are a team in the National Women's Soccer League (NWSL).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] They previously played in Women's Professional Soccer (WPS), of which they were a founding member, before joining the NWSL in 2013.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] They play at SeatGeek Stadium in Bridgeview, Illinois.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Sky is a professional basketball team playing in the Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] They play home games at the Wintrust Arena.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The team was founded before the 2006 WNBA season began.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Marathon has been held each year since 1977 except for 1987, when a half marathon was run in its place.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Marathon is one of six World Marathon Majors.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Street Course in downtown Chicago had races in the Cup Series and Xfinity Series from 2023 to 2025, while the often forgotten Chicago Motor Speedway held CART and NASCAR Truck Series races.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has also entered into esports with the creation of the OpTic Chicago, a professional Call of Duty team that participates within the CDL.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] When Chicago was incorporated in 1837, it chose the motto *Urbs in Horto*, a Latin phrase which means "City in a Garden".
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Today, the Chicago Park District consists of more than 570 parks with over 8,000 acres (3,200 ha) of municipal parkland.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] There are 31 sand beaches, a plethora of museums, two world-class conservatories, and 50 nature areas.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Lincoln Park, the largest of the city's parks, covers 1,200 acres (490 ha) and has over 20 million visitors each year, making it third in the number of visitors after Central Park in New York City, and the National Mall and Memorial Parks in Washington, D.C.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] There is a historic boulevard system, a network of wide, tree-lined boulevards which connect a number of Chicago parks.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The boulevards and the parks were authorized by the Illinois legislature in 1869.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A number of Chicago neighborhoods emerged along these roadways in the 19th century.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The building of the boulevard system continued intermittently until 1942.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] It includes nineteen boulevards, eight parks, and six squares, along twenty-six miles of interconnected streets.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The *Chicago Park Boulevard System Historic District* was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2018.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] With berths for more than 6,000 boats, the Chicago Park District operates the nation's largest municipal harbor system.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Washington Park is also one of the city's biggest parks; covering nearly 400 acres (160 ha).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The park is listed on the National Register of Historic Places listings in South Side Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The government of the City of Chicago is divided into executive and legislative branches.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The mayor of Chicago is the chief executive, elected by general election for a term of four years, with no term limits.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The mayor appoints commissioners and other officials who oversee the various departments.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] As well as the mayor, Chicago's clerk and treasurer are also elected citywide.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The City Council is the legislative branch and is made up of 50 alderpersons, one elected from each ward in the city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The council takes official action through the passage of ordinances and resolutions and approves the city budget.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Police Department provides law enforcement and the Chicago Fire Department provides fire suppression and emergency medical services for the city and its residents.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Civil and criminal law cases are heard in the Cook County Circuit Court of the State of Illinois court system, or in the Northern District of Illinois, in the federal system.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In the state court, the public prosecutor is the Illinois state's attorney; in the Federal court it is the United States attorney.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] During much of the last half of the 19th century, Chicago's politics were dominated by a growing Democratic Party organization.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] During the 1880s and 1890s, Chicago had a powerful radical tradition with large and highly organized socialist, anarchist and labor organizations.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] For much of the 20th century, Chicago has been among the largest and most reliable Democratic strongholds in the United States; with Chicago's Democratic vote the state of Illinois has been "solid blue" in presidential elections since 1992.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Even before then, it was not unheard of for Republican presidential candidates to win handily in downstate Illinois, only to lose statewide due to large Democratic margins in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The citizens of Chicago have not elected a Republican mayor since 1927, when William Thompson was voted into office.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The strength of the party in Chicago is partly a consequence of Illinois state politics, where the Republicans have come to represent rural and farm concerns while the Democrats support urban issues such as Chicago's public school funding.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago contains less than 25% of the state's population, but it is split between eight of Illinois' 17 districts in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] All eight of the city's representatives are Democrats; only two Republicans have represented a significant portion of the city since 1973, for one term each: Robert P.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Hanrahan from 1973 to 1975, and Michael Patrick Flanagan from 1995 to 1997.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Machine politics persisted in Chicago after the decline of similar machines in other large U.S. cities.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] During much of that time, the city administration found opposition mainly from a liberal "independent" faction of the Democratic Party.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The independents finally gained control of city government in 1983 with the election of Harold Washington (in office 1983–1987).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] From 1989 until May 16, 2011, Chicago was under the leadership of its longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Because of the dominance of the Democratic Party in Chicago, the Democratic primary vote held in the spring is generally more significant than the general elections in November for U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The aldermanic, mayoral, and other city offices are filled through nonpartisan elections with runoffs as needed.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city is home of former United States President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama; Barack Obama was formerly a state legislator representing Chicago and later a U.S. senator.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Obamas' residence is located near the University of Chicago in Kenwood on the city's south side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago experienced major rises in violent crime in the 1920s, in the late 1960s, and in the 2020s.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's biggest criminal justice challenges have changed little over the last 50 years, and statistically reside with homicide, armed robbery, gang violence, and aggravated battery.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has a higher murder rate than the larger cities of New York and Los Angeles.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] However, while it has a large absolute number of crimes due to its size, Chicago is not among the top-25 most violent cities in the United States.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Murder rates in Chicago vary greatly depending on the neighborhood in question.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The neighborhoods of Englewood on the South Side, and Austin on the West side, for example, have homicide rates that are ten times higher than other parts of the city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has an estimated population of over 100,000 active gang members from nearly 60 factions.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] According to reports in 2013, "most of Chicago's violent crime comes from gangs trying to maintain control of drug-selling territories," and is specifically related to the activities of the Sinaloa Cartel, which is active in several American cities.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Violent crime rates vary significantly by area of the city, with more economically developed areas having low rates, but other sections have much higher rates of crime.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In 2013, the violent crime rate was 910 per 100,000 people; the murder rate was 10.4 per 100,000 – while high crime districts saw 38.9 murders, low crime districts saw 2.5 murders per 100,000.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago's long history of public corruption regularly draws the attention of federal law enforcement and federal prosecutors.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] From 2012 to 2019, 33 Chicago alderpersons were convicted on corruption charges, roughly one third of those elected in the time period.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A report from the Office of the Legislative Inspector General noted that over half of Chicago's elected alderpersons took illegal campaign contributions in 2013.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Most corruption cases in Chicago are prosecuted by the U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Attorney's office, as legal jurisdiction makes most offenses punishable as a federal crime.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago Public Schools (CPS) is the governing body of the school district that contains over 600 public elementary and high schools citywide, including several selective-admission magnet schools.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] There are eleven selective enrollment high schools in the Chicago Public Schools, designed to meet the needs of Chicago's most academically advanced students.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] These schools offer a rigorous curriculum with mainly honors and Advanced Placement (AP) courses.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Walter Payton College Prep High School is ranked number one in the city of Chicago and the state of Illinois.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago high school rankings are determined by the average test scores on state achievement tests.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The district, with an enrollment exceeding 400,545 students (2013–2014 20th Day Enrollment), is the third-largest in the U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] In September 2012, teachers for the Chicago Teachers Union went on strike for the first time since 1987 over pay, resources, and other issues.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] According to 2014 data, Chicago's "choice system", where students who test or apply and may attend one of approximately 130 public high schools, sorts students of different achievement levels into different schools (high performing, middle performing, and low performing schools).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has a network of Lutheran schools, and several private schools are run by other denominations and faiths, such as the Ida Crown Jewish Academy in West Ridge.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago operates Catholic schools, including Jesuit preparatory schools and others.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] A number of private schools are completely secular.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] There is also the private Chicago Academy for the Arts, a high school focused on six different artistic disciplines, and the public Chicago High School for the Arts, a high school focused on five disciplines (visual arts, theatre, musical theatre, dance, and music).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago Public Library system operates three regional libraries and 77 neighborhood branches, including the central library.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Since the 1850s, Chicago has been a world center of higher education and research with several universities.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] These institutions consistently rank among the top "National Universities" in the United States, as determined by *U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Highly regarded universities in Chicago and the surrounding area are the University of Chicago; Northwestern University; Illinois Institute of Technology; Loyola University Chicago; DePaul University; Columbia College Chicago and the University of Illinois Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] William Rainey Harper, the first president of the University of Chicago, was instrumental in the creation of the junior college concept, establishing nearby Joliet Junior College as the first in the nation in 1901.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] His legacy continues with the multiple community colleges in the Chicago proper, including the seven City Colleges of Chicago: Richard J.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Daley College, Kennedy–King College, Malcolm X College, Olive–Harvey College, Truman College, Harold Washington College, and Wilbur Wright College, in addition to the privately held MacCormac College.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area is a major media hub and the third-largest media market in the United States, after New York City and Los Angeles.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Each of the big five U.S. television networks, NBC, ABC, CBS, Fox and The CW, directly owns and operates a high-definition television station in Chicago (WMAQ 5, WLS 7, WBBM 2, WFLD 32 and WGN-TV 9, respectively).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] WGN is owned by the CW through a majority stake held in the network by the Nexstar Media Group, which acquired it from its founding owner Tribune Broadcasting in 2019.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] WGN was once carried, with some programming differences, as "WGN America" on cable and satellite TV nationwide and in parts of the Caribbean.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] WGN America eventually became NewsNation in 2021.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has been the home of several prominent talk shows, including *The Oprah Winfrey Show*, *Steve Harvey Show*, *The Rosie Show*, *The Jerry Springer Show*, *The Phil Donahue Show*, *The Jenny Jones Show*, and more.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The city has one PBS member station (its second: WYCC 20, removed its affiliation with PBS in 2017): WTTW 11, producer of shows such as *Sneak Previews*, *The Frugal Gourmet*, *Lamb Chop's Play-Along* and *The McLaughlin Group*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] As of 2018, *Windy City Live* is Chicago's only daytime talk show, which is hosted by Val Warner and Ryan Chiaverini at ABC7 Studios with a live weekday audience.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Since 1999, *Judge Mathis* also films his syndicated arbitration-based reality court show at the NBC Tower.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Beginning in January 2019, *Newsy* began producing 12 of its 14 hours of live news programming per day from its new facility in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Most of Chicago's television stations are owned and operated by the big television network companies.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Two major daily newspapers are published in Chicago: the *Chicago Tribune* and the *Chicago Sun-Times*, with the Tribune having the larger circulation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] The entertainment and cultural magazine *Time Out Chicago* and *GRAB* magazine are published in the city, as well as local music magazine *Chicago Innerview*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is the home of satirical national news outlet, *The Onion*, and its sister pop-culture publication, *The A.V.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago has five 50,000 watt AM radio stations: the Audacy-owned WBBM and WSCR; the Tribune Broadcasting-owned WGN; the Cumulus Media-owned WLS; and the ESPN Radio-owned WMVP.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] Chicago is also home to a number of national radio shows, including *Beyond the Beltway* with Bruce DuMont on Sunday evenings.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p02] WBEZ produces nationally aired programs such as PRI's *This American Life* and NPR's *Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!*.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is a major transportation hub in the United States and North America.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] It is an important component in global distribution, as it is the third-largest inter-modal port in the world after Hong Kong and Singapore.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The city of Chicago has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In 2015, 26.5 percent of Chicago households were without a car, and increased slightly to 27.5 percent in 2016.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago averaged 1.12 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Due to Chicago's wheel tax, residents of Chicago who own a vehicle are required to purchase a Chicago City Vehicle Sticker.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In established Residential Parking Zones, only local residents can purchase Zone-specific parking stickers for themselves and guests.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago since 2009 has relinquished rights to its public street parking.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In 2008, as Chicago struggled to close a growing budget deficit, the city agreed to a 75-year, $1.16 billion deal to lease its parking meter system to an operating company created by Morgan Stanley, called Chicago Parking Meters LLC.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The rights of the parking ticket lease end in 2081, and since 2022 have already recouped over $1.5 billion in revenue for Chicago Parking Meters LLC investors.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Eight mainline and four auxiliary interstate highways (41 (mostly in Wisconsin), 55, 57, 65 (only in Indiana), 80 (also in Indiana), 88, 90 (also in Indiana), 94 (also in Indiana), 190, 290, 294, and 355) run through Chicago and its suburbs.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] I-490 is currently under construction on the west side of O'Hare Airport.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Segments that link to the city center are named after influential politicians, with three of them named after former U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Presidents (Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Reagan) and one named after two-time Democratic candidate Adlai Stevenson.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Kennedy and Dan Ryan Expressways are the busiest state maintained routes in the entire state of Illinois.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Regional Transportation Authority (RTA) coordinates the operation of the three service boards: CTA, Metra, and Pace.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Beginning in June 2026, the RTA will be replaced by the Northern Illinois Transit Authority (NITA).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Northern Indiana Commuter Transportation District (NICTD) operates the South Shore Line, which provides commuter rail service from Millennium Station to Northwest Indiana.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Since March 2026, it consists of two services: the Lakeshore Corridor to South Bend and the Monon Corridor to Munster/Dyer.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Greyhound Lines provides inter-city bus service to and from the city at the Chicago Bus Station, and Chicago is also the hub for the Midwest network of Megabus.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Amtrak long distance and inter-city rail services originate from Chicago Union Station.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is one of the largest hubs of passenger rail service in the nation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The services terminate in Port Huron, St.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Paul, the San Francisco Area, New York City, New Orleans, Portland, Oregon, Seattle, Miami, Milwaukee, Carbondale, Quincy, Boston, St.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Louis, Kansas City, Grand Rapids, Los Angeles, San Antonio, and Pontiac, Michigan.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Future service will terminate at Moline.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago has a total of four active rail terminals: Chicago Union Station, Ogilvie Transportation Center, LaSalle Street Station, and Millennium Station.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Amtrak only serves Union Station, while Metra serves all four stations.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The South Shore Line services uses Millennium Station as its Chicago terminal.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In July 2013, the bicycle-sharing system Divvy was launched with 750 bikes and 75 docking stations.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] It is operated by Lyft for the Chicago Department of Transportation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] As of July 2019, Divvy operated 5800 bicycles at 608 stations, covering almost all of the city, excluding Pullman, Rosedale, Beverly, Belmont Cragin and Edison Park.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In May 2019, The City of Chicago announced its Chicago's Electric Shared Scooter Pilot Program, scheduled to run from June 15 to October 15.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The program started on June 15 with 10 different scooter companies, including scooter sharing market leaders Bird, Jump, Lime and Lyft.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Each company was allowed to bring 250 electric scooters, although both Bird and Lime claimed that they experienced a higher demand for their scooters.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The program ended on October 15, with nearly 800,000 rides taken.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is the largest hub in the railroad industry.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] All five Class I railroads meet in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] As of 2002, severe freight train congestion caused trains to take as long to get through the Chicago region as it took to get there from the West Coast of the country (about 2 days).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Department of Transportation, the volume of imported and exported goods transported via rail to, from, or through Chicago is forecast to increase nearly 150 percent between 2010 and 2040.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] CREATE, the Chicago Region Environmental and Transportation Efficiency Program, comprises about 70 programs, including crossovers, overpasses and underpasses, that intend to significantly improve the speed of freight movements in the Chicago area.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Chicago is served by O'Hare International Airport, the world's busiest airport measured by airline operations, on the far Northwest Side, and Midway International Airport on the Southwest Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In 2005, O'Hare was the world's busiest airport by aircraft movements and the second-busiest by total passenger traffic.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] O'Hare is major hub for American Airlines and United Airlines.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Midway is a major operating base for Southwest Airlines.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Both O'Hare and Midway are owned and operated by the City of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The CTA's Blue Line provides direct rail access to O'Hare, while the Orange Line provides direct rail access to Midway.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Gary/Chicago International Airport and Chicago Rockford International Airport, located in Gary, Indiana and Rockford, Illinois, respectively, can serve as alternative Chicago area airports, however they do not offer as many commercial flights as O'Hare and Midway.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In recent years the state of Illinois has been leaning towards building an entirely new airport in the Illinois suburbs of Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The City of Chicago is the world headquarters for United Airlines, the world's third-largest airline.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Port of Chicago consists of several major port facilities within the city of Chicago operated by the Illinois International Port District (formerly known as the Chicago Regional Port District).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The central element of the Port District, Calumet Harbor, is maintained by the U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Electricity for most of northern Illinois is provided by Commonwealth Edison, also known as ComEd.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Their service territory borders Iroquois County to the south, the Wisconsin border to the north, the Iowa border to the west and the Indiana border to the east.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In northern Illinois, ComEd (a division of Exelon) operates the greatest number of nuclear generating plants in any U.S. state.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Because of this, ComEd reports indicate that Chicago receives about 75% of its electricity from nuclear power.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Recently, the city began installing wind turbines on government buildings to promote renewable energy.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Natural gas is provided by Peoples Gas, a subsidiary of Integrys Energy Group, which is headquartered in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Domestic and industrial waste was once incinerated but it is now landfilled, mainly in the Calumet area.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] From 1995 to 2008, the city had a blue bag program to divert recyclable refuse from landfills.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Because of low participation in the blue bag programs, the city began a pilot program for blue bin recycling like other cities.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] This proved successful and blue bins were rolled out across the city.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Illinois Medical District is on the Near West Side.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] It includes Rush University Medical Center, ranked as the second best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] News & World Report* for 2014–16, the University of Illinois Medical Center at Chicago, Jesse Brown VA Hospital, and John H.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Hospital of Cook County, one of the busiest trauma centers in the nation.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] Two of the country's premier academic medical centers, Northwestern Memorial Hospital and the University of Chicago Medical Center, reside in Chicago.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Chicago campus of Northwestern University includes the Feinberg School of Medicine; Northwestern Memorial Hospital, which was ranked as the best hospital in the Chicago metropolitan area by *U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] News & World Report* for 2017–18; the Shirley Ryan AbilityLab (formerly named the Rehabilitation Institute of Chicago), which was ranked the best U.S. rehabilitation hospital by *U.S.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] News & World Report*; the new Prentice Women's Hospital; and Ann & Robert H.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The University of Illinois College of Medicine at UIC is the second-largest medical school in the United States (2,600 students, including those at campuses in Peoria, Rockford and Urbana–Champaign).
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] In addition, the Chicago Medical School and Loyola University Chicago's Stritch School of Medicine are located in the suburbs of North Chicago and Maywood, respectively.
[src:fred-kommers/chicago-illinois-p03] The Midwestern University Chicago College of Osteopathic Medicine is in Downers Grove.
